  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="FR">Burundi: upholding human rights in a repressive context</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="FR">Burundi experienced a civil war from 1993 to 2005, as a result of long-standing ethnic divisions between the Hutu and the Tutsi ethnic groups. The Arusha Accords of 2000 re-established a governance structure, with power sharing by Hutus and Tutsis, and integration of former rebels and minority groups into the Burundian army. Pierre Nkurunziza of the CNDD-FDD party became the president of Burundi in 2005. After two terms, Nkurunziza was controversially nominated for a third term in office. This sparked nation-wide protests, which were violently repressed. On the 13th of May, a coup took place, which was reversed by the 15th of May 2015. Since then, repression against opponents and civil society groups has worsened, to the extent that all human rights groups went into exile; many of the leaders went to Rwanda, Uganda or Tanzania. Nkurunziza agreed not to stand for a fourth term; the ruling party nominated Evariste Ndayishimiye as the new presidential candidate, who actually won the Presidential elections in May 2020. Only days after the vote, on 8 June, Nkurunziza died of supposedly a cardiac arrest. The new president continued the repressive policies of his predecessor.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="FR">HURICAP has worked in Burundi since 2010. Its long-term programme with a network of CSOs came to an end in 2015. Smaller projects with individual organisations were supported as of 2016. However, with the removal of most human rights organisations from the country and the  fact that Amnesty International was no longer allowed into the country because of its critical stance against these repressive measures, as well as the lack of performance of the few remaining partners, HURICAP wanted to stop its work in the country altogether, until it came into contact with DefendDefenders, who asked MDR support to train monitors linked to exiled CSOs. In 2019, a collaboration was explored and discussed, to engage in a pilot project for remote/online training and coaching to monitors within Burundi. Implementation of the pilot started in 2020.</narrative>
  </description>
